<subSubSection id="84882391A52D6A07B8CDFC67FEF3FB9A" pageId="2" pageNumber="1089" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="CC2D701AA52D6A07B8CDFC67FEF3FB9A" blockId="2.[178,1085,955,1035]" pageId="2" pageNumber="1089">Etymology: The specific epithet is an adjective composed of the Latin prefix bi- (two) and the Latin adjective virgatus (striped). It alludes to the pair of reddish bands on the elytra.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="84882391A52D6A00B8CDFBC7FEDDFE25" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="1092" pageId="2" pageNumber="1089" type="description">
<paragraph id="CC2D701AA52D6A07B8CDFBC7FCCAFB34" blockId="2.[178,1085,1050,1190]" pageId="2" pageNumber="1089">
Description: Body length 5.4-6.0 mm; length of forebody 
<quantity id="0B6ADDFFA52D6A07BB16FBC7FC0FFBA1" box="[873,996,1051,1072]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.95" metricValueMax="3.1" metricValueMin="2.8" pageId="2" pageNumber="1089" unit="mm" value="2.95" valueMax="3.1" valueMin="2.8">2.8-3.1 mm</quantity>
. Species of slender habitus (
<figureCitation id="54A96C9FA52D6A07B901FBE4FE56FBDF" box="[382,445,1080,1102]" captionStart="Figs 1-7" captionStartId="3.[178,218,1518,1540]" captionTargetBox="[195,1055,212,1485]" captionTargetId="figure-1@3.[178,1082,212,1493]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 1-7: Echiaster bivirgatus nov.sp. (1-2, 4-5: holotype; 3, 6-7: paratype from North India): (1) habitus; (2-3) forebody; (4-7) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 1-3: 1.0 mm; 4-7: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5361371" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5361371/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="1089">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Coloration: forebody dark-brown to blackish-brown, elytra each with a long, often slightly curved reddish band of variable width extending from the humeral angles to the posterior margin, or nearly so; abdomen blackish; legs yellowish; antennae yellowish-red to reddish with brown antennomere I.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CC2D701AA52D6A07B8CDFB69FC08FAD1" blockId="2.[178,1085,1205,1344]" pageId="2" pageNumber="1089">
Head (
<figureCitation id="54A96C9FA52D6A07B883FB69FEB2FB5A" box="[252,345,1205,1227]" captionStart="Figs 1-7" captionStartId="3.[178,218,1518,1540]" captionTargetBox="[195,1055,212,1485]" captionTargetId="figure-1@3.[178,1082,212,1493]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 1-7: Echiaster bivirgatus nov.sp. (1-2, 4-5: holotype; 3, 6-7: paratype from North India): (1) habitus; (2-3) forebody; (4-7) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 1-3: 1.0 mm; 4-7: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5361371" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5361371/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="1089">Figs 2-3</figureCitation>
) approximately as broad as long, widest across eyes, behind eyes convexly narrowed towards neck in dorsal view; posterior angles obsolete; punctation coarse, areolate, and extremely dense; interstices reduced to narrow ridges; dorsal surface matt. Eyes conspicuously large, nearly as long as distance from posterior margin of eye to posterior constriction of head in dorsal view. Antenna short, 1.0- 
<quantity id="0B6ADDFFA52D6A07BB23FAF6FC42FAD1" box="[860,937,1322,1344]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" pageId="2" pageNumber="1089" unit="mm" value="1.1">1.1 mm</quantity>
long.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CC2D701AA52D6A07B8CDFA8CFDEBFA2C" blockId="2.[178,1085,1359,1469]" pageId="2" pageNumber="1089">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation id="54A96C9FA52D6A07B958FA93FE6BFAF4" box="[295,384,1359,1381]" captionStart="Figs 1-7" captionStartId="3.[178,218,1518,1540]" captionTargetBox="[195,1055,212,1485]" captionTargetId="figure-1@3.[178,1082,212,1493]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 1-7: Echiaster bivirgatus nov.sp. (1-2, 4-5: holotype; 3, 6-7: paratype from North India): (1) habitus; (2-3) forebody; (4-7) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 1-3: 1.0 mm; 4-7: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5361371" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5361371/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="1089">Figs 2-3</figureCitation>
) slender, approximately 1.4 times as long as broad and 0.71-0.75 times as broad as head; median portion shallowly impressed in posterior two thirds, this impression with median elevation in posterior third of pronotum; punctation similar to that of head, but slightly coarser.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CC2D701AA52D6A07B8CDFA10FBC8F9AB" blockId="2.[178,1085,1484,1594]" pageId="2" pageNumber="1089">
Elytra (
<figureCitation id="54A96C9FA52D6A07B880FA10FEBDFA72" box="[255,342,1484,1507]" captionStart="Figs 1-7" captionStartId="3.[178,218,1518,1540]" captionTargetBox="[195,1055,212,1485]" captionTargetId="figure-1@3.[178,1082,212,1493]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 1-7: Echiaster bivirgatus nov.sp. (1-2, 4-5: holotype; 3, 6-7: paratype from North India): (1) habitus; (2-3) forebody; (4-7) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 1-3: 1.0 mm; 4-7: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5361371" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5361371/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="1089">Figs 2-3</figureCitation>
) dimorphic, approximately 0.85 times as long and 1.4 times as broad as pronotum in macropterous morph, approximately 0.65 times as long and 1.3 times as broad as pronotum in brachypterous morph; humeral angles pronounced in macropterous morph, less pronounced in brachypterous morph; punctation very dense and granulose.
</paragraph>
<caption id="98ED2092A52C6A06B8CDFA32FF15F9A0" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5361371" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5361371" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5361371/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="1090" startId="3.[178,218,1518,1540]" targetBox="[195,1055,212,1485]" targetPageId="3">
<paragraph id="CC2D701AA52C6A06B8CDFA32FF15F9A0" blockId="3.[178,1086,1518,1585]" pageId="3" pageNumber="1090">
<emphasis id="FEE6AC08A52C6A06B8CDFA32FEEBF992" bold="true" box="[178,256,1518,1540]" pageId="3" pageNumber="1090">Figs 1-7</emphasis>
: 
<taxonomicName id="0B920B99A52C6A06B971FA33FE23F995" authority="Assing &amp; I, 2014" authorityName="Assing &amp; I" authorityYear="2014" box="[270,456,1519,1540]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Echiaster" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="1090" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bivirgatus" status="nov.sp.">
<emphasis id="FEE6AC08A52C6A06B971FA33FE23F995" box="[270,456,1519,1540]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="1090">Echiaster bivirgatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="E5D51173A52C6A06B9AFFA33FDF9F995" box="[464,530,1519,1540]" pageId="3" pageNumber="1090" rank="species">nov.sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
(
<emphasis id="FEE6AC08A52C6A06BA5FFA32FDD4F992" bold="true" box="[544,575,1518,1539]" pageId="3" pageNumber="1090">1-2</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis id="FEE6AC08A52C6A06BA33FA32FD81F992" bold="true" box="[588,618,1518,1539]" pageId="3" pageNumber="1090">4-5</emphasis>
: holotype; 
<emphasis id="FEE6AC08A52C6A06BAAAFA32FD0BF992" bold="true" box="[725,736,1518,1539]" pageId="3" pageNumber="1090">3</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis id="FEE6AC08A52C6A06BA91FA32FCE7F992" bold="true" box="[750,780,1518,1539]" pageId="3" pageNumber="1090">6-7</emphasis>
: paratype from North India): (
<emphasis id="FEE6AC08A52C6A06BC55FA32FBDEF992" bold="true" box="[1066,1077,1518,1539]" pageId="3" pageNumber="1090">1</emphasis>
) habitus; (
<emphasis id="FEE6AC08A52C6A06B977F9D9FEC5F98A" bold="true" box="[264,302,1541,1563]" pageId="3" pageNumber="1090">2-3)</emphasis>
forebody; (
<emphasis id="FEE6AC08A52C6A06B9E5F9D9FE53F98B" bold="true" box="[410,440,1541,1562]" pageId="3" pageNumber="1090">4-7</emphasis>
) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 1-3: 1.0 mm; 4-7: 0.2 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<caption id="98ED2092A52B6A01B8CDFB04FC78FA8A" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5361373" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5361373" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5361373/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="1091" startId="4.[178,218,1240,1262]" targetBox="[178,1033,225,1219]" targetPageId="4">
<paragraph id="CC2D701AA52B6A01B8CDFB04FC78FA8A" blockId="4.[178,1085,1240,1308]" pageId="4" pageNumber="1091">
<emphasis id="FEE6AC08A52B6A01B8CDFB04FEE1FB7C" bold="true" box="[178,266,1240,1262]" pageId="4" pageNumber="1091">Figs 8-13</emphasis>
: 
<taxonomicName id="0B920B99A52B6A01B969FB04FE24FB7C" authority="Assing &amp; I, 2014" authorityName="Assing &amp; I" authorityYear="2014" box="[278,463,1240,1261]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Echiaster" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="1091" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bivirgatus" status="nov.sp.">
<emphasis id="FEE6AC08A52B6A01B969FB04FE24FB7C" box="[278,463,1240,1261]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="1091">Echiaster bivirgatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="E5D51173A52B6A01B9ABFB05FDF2FB7F" box="[468,537,1241,1262]" pageId="4" pageNumber="1091" rank="species">nov.sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, holotype (
<emphasis id="FEE6AC08A52B6A01BA01FB04FD77FB7C" bold="true" box="[638,668,1240,1261]" pageId="4" pageNumber="1091">8-9</emphasis>
) and 
<taxonomicName id="0B920B99A52B6A01BAAFFB05FCBFFB7C" authority="Assing &amp; I, 2014" authorityName="Assing &amp; I" authorityYear="2014" box="[720,852,1240,1262]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Echiaster" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="1091" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paulexcisus" status="nov.sp.">
<emphasis id="FEE6AC08A52B6A01BAAFFB05FCBFFB7C" box="[720,852,1240,1262]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="1091">E. paulexcisus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="E5D51173A52B6A01BB26FB05FC77FB7F" box="[857,924,1241,1262]" pageId="4" pageNumber="1091" rank="species">nov.sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
(
<emphasis id="FEE6AC08A52B6A01BBD7FB04FC36FB7C" bold="true" box="[936,989,1240,1261]" pageId="4" pageNumber="1091">10-13</emphasis>
): (
<emphasis id="FEE6AC08A52B6A01BB87FB04FBE8FB7C" bold="true" box="[1016,1027,1240,1261]" pageId="4" pageNumber="1091">8</emphasis>
) male sternite VII; (
<emphasis id="FEE6AC08A52B6A01B94CFB33FED5FA95" bold="true" box="[307,318,1263,1284]" pageId="4" pageNumber="1091">9</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis id="FEE6AC08A52B6A01B932FB33FE8FFA95" bold="true" box="[333,356,1263,1284]" pageId="4" pageNumber="1091">11</emphasis>
) male sternite VIII; (
<emphasis id="FEE6AC08A52B6A01BA4EFB33FDBBFA94" bold="true" box="[561,592,1263,1285]" pageId="4" pageNumber="1091">10)</emphasis>
forebody; (
<emphasis id="FEE6AC08A52B6A01BABFFB33FD3CFA95" bold="true" box="[704,727,1263,1284]" pageId="4" pageNumber="1091">12</emphasis>
) aedeagus in lateral view; (
<emphasis id="FEE6AC08A52B6A01BB9FFB33FC1CFA95" bold="true" box="[992,1015,1263,1284]" pageId="4" pageNumber="1091">13</emphasis>
) apical portion of aedeagus in ventral view. Scale bars: 10: 1.0 mm; 8-9, 11-13: 0.2 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="CC2D701AA52B6A01B8CDFAF5FDE1FA5A" blockId="4.[178,1086,1321,1483]" pageId="4" pageNumber="1091">
Abdomen little more than 0.9 times as broad as elytra (macropterous morph) or broader than elytra (brachypterous morph), broadest at base, gradually tapering posteriad (
<figureCitation id="54A96C9FA52B6A01BC6BFA99FF55FAE6" captionStart="Figs 1-7" captionStartId="3.[178,218,1518,1540]" captionTargetBox="[195,1055,212,1485]" captionTargetId="figure-1@3.[178,1082,212,1493]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 1-7: Echiaster bivirgatus nov.sp. (1-2, 4-5: holotype; 3, 6-7: paratype from North India): (1) habitus; (2-3) forebody; (4-7) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 1-3: 1.0 mm; 4-7: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5361371" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5361371/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="1091">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
); tergites III-V with very coarse and dense punctation; tergites VI-VIII with dense and fine punctation; posterior margin of tergite VII strongly convex, with palisade fringe both in macropterous and in brachypterous morph; tergite VIII distinctly oblong and with strongly convex posterior margin.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CC2D701AA52B6A01B8B8FA05FD5BF9D3" blockId="4.[178,1085,1497,1603]" pageId="4" pageNumber="1091">
: sternite VII (
<figureCitation id="54A96C9FA52B6A01B923FA05FE70FA7E" box="[348,411,1497,1519]" captionStart="Figs 8-13" captionStartId="4.[178,218,1240,1262]" captionTargetBox="[178,1033,225,1219]" captionTargetId="figure-1@4.[178,1071,212,1231]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 8-13: Echiaster bivirgatus nov.sp., holotype (8-9) and E. paulexcisus nov.sp. (10-13): (8) male sternite VII; (9, 11) male sternite VIII; (10) forebody; (12) aedeagus in lateral view; (13) apical portion of aedeagus in ventral view. Scale bars: 10: 1.0 mm; 8-9, 11-13: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5361373" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5361373/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="1091">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
) slender, as long as broad and with very dense dark pubescence, posterior margin weakly concave; sternite VIII (
<figureCitation id="54A96C9FA52B6A01BAC4FA29FD17F99A" box="[699,764,1525,1547]" captionStart="Figs 8-13" captionStartId="4.[178,218,1240,1262]" captionTargetBox="[178,1033,225,1219]" captionTargetId="figure-1@4.[178,1071,212,1231]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 8-13: Echiaster bivirgatus nov.sp., holotype (8-9) and E. paulexcisus nov.sp. (10-13): (8) male sternite VII; (9, 11) male sternite VIII; (10) forebody; (12) aedeagus in lateral view; (13) apical portion of aedeagus in ventral view. Scale bars: 10: 1.0 mm; 8-9, 11-13: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5361373" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5361373/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="1091">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
) distinctly oblong, nearly 1.3 times as long as broad, posterior margin convex and in the middle weakly concave; aedeagus 
<quantity id="0B6ADDFFA52B6A01B96AF9F1FE84F9D3" box="[277,367,1581,1603]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.7" pageId="4" pageNumber="1091" unit="mm" value="0.67">0.67 mm</quantity>
long and shaped as in 
<figureCitation id="54A96C9FA52B6A01BA2AF9F1FD5BF9D3" box="[597,688,1581,1603]" captionStart="Figs 1-7" captionStartId="3.[178,218,1518,1540]" captionTargetBox="[195,1055,212,1485]" captionTargetId="figure-1@3.[178,1082,212,1493]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 1-7: Echiaster bivirgatus nov.sp. (1-2, 4-5: holotype; 3, 6-7: paratype from North India): (1) habitus; (2-3) forebody; (4-7) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 1-3: 1.0 mm; 4-7: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5361371" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5361371/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="1091">Figs 4-7.</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CC2D701AA52A6A00B8CDFF06FEDDFE25" blockId="5.[178,1085,218,436]" pageId="5" pageNumber="1092">
Intraspecific variation: The specimens from North 
<collectingCountry id="B485308AA52A6A00BBD1FF06FC09FF61" box="[942,994,218,240]" name="India" pageId="5" pageNumber="1092">India</collectingCountry>
are all brachypterous and have elytra with a broad, nearly straight longitudinal reddish band on both elytra, whereas those from 
<collectingCountry id="B485308AA52A6A00BA74FECEFD8EFEB9" box="[523,613,274,296]" name="Thailand" pageId="5" pageNumber="1092">Thailand</collectingCountry>
are all macropterous and have elytra with a very narrow and somewhat curved longitudinal reddish band (
<figureCitation id="54A96C9FA52A6A00BB40FEF2FC71FED5" box="[831,922,302,324]" captionStart="Figs 1-7" captionStartId="3.[178,218,1518,1540]" captionTargetBox="[195,1055,212,1485]" captionTargetId="figure-1@3.[178,1082,212,1493]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 1-7: Echiaster bivirgatus nov.sp. (1-2, 4-5: holotype; 3, 6-7: paratype from North India): (1) habitus; (2-3) forebody; (4-7) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 1-3: 1.0 mm; 4-7: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5361371" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5361371/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="1092">Figs 2-3</figureCitation>
). The aedeagus (
<figureCitation id="54A96C9FA52A6A00B8C6FE96FEFEFEF1" box="[185,277,330,352]" captionStart="Figs 1-7" captionStartId="3.[178,218,1518,1540]" captionTargetBox="[195,1055,212,1485]" captionTargetId="figure-1@3.[178,1082,212,1493]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 1-7: Echiaster bivirgatus nov.sp. (1-2, 4-5: holotype; 3, 6-7: paratype from North India): (1) habitus; (2-3) forebody; (4-7) aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view. Scale bars: 1-3: 1.0 mm; 4-7: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5361371" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5361371/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="1092">Figs 4-7</figureCitation>
), however, is very similar, so that the observed differences are attributed to intra- rather than interspecific variation. Unfortunately, the abdominal sternite VIII of the sole male from 
<collectingCountry id="B485308AA52A6A00B920FE5EFE78FE09" box="[351,403,386,408]" name="India" pageId="5" pageNumber="1092">India</collectingCountry>
had been completely destroyed and was thus not available for examination.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="84882391A52A6A00B8CDFE1EFE52FD11" pageId="5" pageNumber="1092" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="CC2D701AA52A6A00B8CDFE1EFE52FD11" blockId="5.[178,1086,450,640]" pageId="5" pageNumber="1092">
Comparative notes: The new species is easily distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="0B920B99A52A6A00BC58FE1EFEE3FE62" authorityName="BERNHAUER" authorityYear="1922" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Echiaster" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="1092" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="unicolor">
<emphasis id="FEE6AC08A52A6A00BC58FE1EFEE3FE62" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="1092">E. unicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="0B920B99A52A6A00B940FE02FE77FE62" authorityName="ASSING" authorityYear="2013" box="[319,412,478,499]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Echiaster" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="1092" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maior">
<emphasis id="FEE6AC08A52A6A00B940FE02FE77FE62" box="[319,412,478,499]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="1092">E. maior</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by numerous characters, particularly the larger eyes, the longer and differently coloured elytra, the more distinctly conical abdomen, the presence of a palisade fringe at the posterior margin of the male tergite VII, the more slender male sternite VII, the much shallower posterior excision of the male sternite VIII, and by the completely different morphology of the aedeagus. For illustrations of 
<taxonomicName id="0B920B99A52A6A00BBFFFD92FC1FFDF2" authorityName="BERNHAUER" authorityYear="1922" box="[896,1012,590,611]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Echiaster" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="1092" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="unicolor">
<emphasis id="FEE6AC08A52A6A00BBFFFD92FC1FFDF2" box="[896,1012,590,611]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="1092">E. unicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="0B920B99A52A6A00BC58FD92FF05FDEE" authorityName="ASSING" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Echiaster" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="1092" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maior">
<emphasis id="FEE6AC08A52A6A00BC58FD92FF05FDEE" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="1092">E. maior</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
see 
<bibRefCitation id="A8030DEBA52A6A00B964FDB6FE5FFD11" author="ASSING V" box="[283,436,618,640]" journalOrPublisher="Linzer biologische Beitrage" pageId="5" pageNumber="1092" pagination="1527 - 1530" part="45" refId="ref4552" refString="ASSING V. (2013): The second species of Echiaster from Asia (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Paederinae). - Linzer biologische Beitrage 45 (2): 1527 - 1530" title="The second species of Echiaster from Asia (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Paederinae)" type="journal article" year="2013">ASSING (2013)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="84882391A52A6A00B8CDFD52FDB6FD69" pageId="5" pageNumber="1092" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="CC2D701AA52A6A00B8CDFD52FDB6FD69" blockId="5.[178,1085,654,760]" pageId="5" pageNumber="1092">
Distribution and natural history: The specimens were collected in four localities in 
<collectingCountry id="B485308AA52A6A00B902FD76FE3CFD51" box="[381,471,682,704]" name="Thailand" pageId="5" pageNumber="1092">Thailand</collectingCountry>
and one in North 
